			        	<section class="spotlight">
			        		<div class="image"><img src="images/fico.jpg" alt="" /></div><div class="content">
			        		<h2><a href="https://www.fico.com/">FICO</a></h2>
			        			<p>
			        			FICO provides analytics software and tools used across multiple industries to manage risk,
			        			fight fraud,
			        			build more profitable customer relationships, optimize operations and meet strict government regulations.
			        			Many of FICO's products reach industry-wide adoption, such as the FICO Score,
			        			the standard measure of consumer credit risk in the United States.
			        			The company also helps millions of people manage their personal credit health.<br />
			        			Founded in 1956, FICO introduced analytic solutions such as credit scoring
			        			that have made credit more widely available, not just in the United States but around the world. 
			        			FICO have pioneered the development and application of critical technologies behind decision management.
			        			These include predictive analytics, business rules management and optimization.
			        			FICO uses these technologies to help businesses improve the precision, consistency and agility of their complex,
			        			high-volume decisions.<br /><br /> </p>
			        		</div>
			        	</section>
			        </section>
			        <section id="Physics" class="wrapper alt style2">
			        	<section class="spotlight">
			        		<div class="image"><img src="images/cern.jpg" alt="" /></div><div class="content">
			        		<h2><a href="https://home.cern/about">CERN Laboratory</a></h2>
			        			<p>I have been often located in Geneva, Switzerland where I used to conduct research
			        			at CERN laboratory (European Council for Nuclear Research).
			        			The CERN laboratory has 22 member states, and it is a dynamical environment where physicists from all
			        			the world collaborate together.
			        			CERN contains the Large Hadron Collider (LHC): the world's largest and most powerful particle accelerator.
			        			The LHC consists of a 27-kilometers ring of superconducting magnets and accelerating structures.
			        			From here, the beams are made to collide at four locations around the accelerator ring,
			        			corresponding to the four experiments: ATLAS, CMS, ALICE and LHCb.<br />
			        			I arrived at CERN to work in CMS for my undergraduate thesis in 2010, and I immediately felt in love with the
			        			stimulating and enriching environment CERN represents.<br /><br /> </p>
			        		</div>
			        	</section>
			        </section>
			        <section id="Physics" class="wrapper alt style2">
			        	<section class="spotlight">
			        		<div class="image"><img src="images/cms.jpg" alt="" /></div><div class="content">
			        		<h2><a href="https://home.cern/about/experiments/cms">CMS Experiment at CERN</a></h2>
			        			<p>The Compact Muon Solenoid (CMS) is a general-purpose detector at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC).
			        			It has a broad physics program ranging from studying the Standard Model (including the Higgs boson)
			        			to searching for extra dimensions and particles that could make up dark matter.<br />
			        			Since I entered the CMS collaboration (formed by more than 6000 physicists and engineers) I worked both in the analysis of
			        			the large amount of data collected by the experiment, and in improving the detector performances.
			        			I served as the manager for the CMS alignment, calibration and databases area, which ensure the correct and 
			        			optimal performance of the detector, and its representation in simulation.
			        			Also, I have been responsible for the alignment of the CMS muon detector that
			        			I represented in the muon Detector Performance Group Office.
			        			I have been active in the Exotic Higgs working group where I led group of graduate students and postdoc in the search
			        			for low mass resonances and dark photons, and in the search for resonant di-Higgs production.<br /><br /> <p\>
			        		</div>
			        	</section>
