								<li class="icon fa-bank">
									<h3><a href="http://mitchell.tamu.edu/events/seminars/phenomenology/">HEPEC Seminars</a></h3>
									<p>From 2015 to 2018 I organized the High Energy Phenomenology Experiment and Cosmology seminar
									at Texas A&M University. Speakers from US and Europe are invited to give a seminar
									on their research topic in our institute.<br/>
									The discussion and exchange of ideas that follow such seminars often help graduate students to gain a 
									broader insight of Physics, and sometimes to build up collaborations across Universities.
									The organization of the seminars has been a very enriching experience.
								</li>
								<li class="icon fa-group">
									<h3><a href="https://visit.cern/tours">CERN Guide</a></h3>
									<p>As an official CERN guide, I lead tours of tourists and students who visit the laboratory.
									I conduct visits in English, Spanish, and Italian.
									My goal is to leave visitors with a better understanding of the importance of fundamental research,
									and curiosity towards High Energy Physics. Since each group of visitors has a different background
									it is very stimulating to adapt the tour depending on the needs of the guests.</p>
								</li>
								<li class="icon fa-paper-plane-o">
									<h3><a href=http://physicsfestival.tamu.edu/">Virtual tour of the Large Hadron Collider</a></h3>
									<p>Texas A&M Physics and Engeneering Festival 
									gathers over 5000 visitors annually from across the United States, thanks to 
									over 200 interactive physics demonstrations, specialized programs by age groups,
									and public lectures by prominent scientists and astronauts.<br/>
									I contribute by organizing a vitual tour of the Large Hadron Colliders,
									where I show to future scientists
									the biggest open questions about our Universe, and how we are planning to answer them thanks to
									data produced byt the Large Hadron collider.
